  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Flat and round are E. M. Forster\u0026rsquo;s terms (from Aspects of the Novel, 1927) for the two basic kinds of character in fiction. A flat character is built around a single trait, quality, or idea. A round character is complex, contradictory, and capable of surprising the reader in a way that is convincing.\nForster\u0026rsquo;s distinction is descriptive, not evaluative — flat characters are not failed round characters. They serve different functions:\n",
